super cool encounter!!! after watching the delaware river, went back going east towards the trail area when I saw an accipiter flying low about 2-3m off the ground heading north from somewhere near the forest edge and then perching on cross structure at the south end of the bridge over the aqueduct, got some photos immediately before walking up to it. to my surprised, one cyclist and another walking person passed right by it, probably 2-3 m from it since its perch was just on the side of the road about 3 m high, and when i got there it didn't fly away immediately either. However when I got camera and stayed there to take photos it probably felt uncomfortable and moved to another perch about 5 m away, but I could still get photos there. it stayed for about 30 seconds before going far away on tall on trees north of the creek of the aqueduct. from this experience I feel like I've learned that sometimes if you just walk by a bird it doesn't fly away but once you stop and look at it, even if you don't move or do anything, it will fly away, so better pretend you're not focusing you attention on them!!  also my best photos of a cooper's hawk yet

Observation Details: Three seen simultaneously. One flew in to a pecan tree carrying prey, pursued by two others. Bird in photo 943 moved in on the ground and flew into the tree, displacing the holder of the carcass, the latter falling to the ground. The original 'owner' of the carcass then flew down to it, mantling and calling.   A Video of mantling bird at https://youtu.be/hV2ZnxIAZXk.  I don't know whether this interaction was of a mated pair, or a territorial scuffle between pairs which nest in the area. I haven't been able to sex the two - since they're the same size, apparently, the interaction may be territorial. It does seem odd that pairs competing for territory would squabble over a carcass. It's a puzzle to me.

Heard the distinctive call of a juvenile COHA shortly after I arrived. Couldn’t locate the bird but after a while I could hear a second calling. After a long wait one of them flew in and landed on a perch above the Annapolis River. Long rounded tail, large head, pale underparts with fine tear-dropped shaped streaks, buffy "bib" of a juvenile. While watching this hawk on the south side of the river, I could hear the second calling, nearby, but on the north side of the river. As I listened I could also hear a third calling, also on the south side, but further west downriver. Eventually the hawk on the north side also flew in and perched above the river. Not long after, the third hawk that I was hearing flew across the river to the north bank, giving me a view of all three at one time. I did not see any adults during the time there.   This is the same location that I found juvenile Cooper’s last year. On July 30, 2020, I heard the calling and determined they were there. I returned on July 31, 2020 and confirmed that there were three, and obtained photos at that time. It’s possible the breeding pair from last year have returned?

Observation Details: Unusual views from a couple of meters directly above; the immature hawk was hunting nearby feeders (mostly flocks of HOSP but also a number of MODOs around) and the pictures were taken immediately after a failed pass at some sparrows on the ground. The bird remained on the ground for a couple of minutes before relocating to the dense internal web of branches in a nearby small tree that frequently holds 100+ birds, where it was extremely concealed. No depredations observed. Immature but fairly large, I'd estimate it to be crow-sized; not sure if this suggests that it's a female.

*high count | exact count. Very interesting behavior. At first noticed one flying over to the brush pile up on the hill and later 2. Then as I was coming up to check it out I saw 5 birds! At first I thought they were all coops but quickly realized that there where 3 coops, 1 sharpie, and 1 rsha... all within 10 feet of each other!  They were also very approachable, especially the red-shouldered, allowing me to get within 15 feet of him (or her)! I have never seen this kind of behavior with any hawks before. Could they have been hunting together??? Or maybe, they were just hanging around in the same area where food was abundant. I think that the coops where probably from this year's brood (I found them nesting in the woods over the hill this spring) since they all were juvys.

Heard the distinctive call of a juvenile COHA shortly after I arrived. Couldn’t locate the bird but after a while I could hear a second calling. After a long wait one of them flew in and landed on a perch above the Annapolis River. Long rounded tail, large head, pale underparts with fine tear-dropped shaped streaks, buffy "bib" of a juvenile. While watching this hawk on the south side of the river, I could hear the second calling, nearby, but on the north side of the river. As I listened I could also hear a third calling, also on the south side, but further west downriver. Eventually the hawk on the north side also flew in and perched above the river. Not long after, the third hawk that I was hearing flew across the river to the north bank, giving me a view of all three at one time. I did not see any adults during the time there.   This is the same location that I found juvenile Cooper’s last year. On July 30, 2020, I heard the calling and determined they were there. I returned on July 31, 2020 and confirmed that there were three, and obtained photos at that time. It’s possible the breeding pair from last year have returned?

In the field, at first sight,  I originally thought the bird  was a sharp-shinned hawk, but I was able to get close to it and determined it was a Cooper's Hawk; probably a juvenile male. I observed the following at close range: rounded tail; yellow eye; squared-head, buff colored; large feet and thick legs; thin, dark streaks on breast and chest. Stiff, choppy wingbeats in flight. It did not have the "bug-eye" appearance of a sharp-shinned hawk.

Locality: Fort Lowell Park and Pantano Wash
Observation Details: Three seen simultaneously. One flew in to a pecan tree carrying prey, pursued by two others. Bird in photo 943 moved in on the ground and flew into the tree, displacing the holder of the carcass, the latter falling to the ground. The original 'owner' of the carcass then flew down to it, mantling and calling.   A Video of mantling bird at https://youtu.be/hV2ZnxIAZXk.  I don't know whether this interaction was of a mated pair, or a territorial scuffle between pairs which nest in the area. I haven't been able to sex the two - since they're the same size, apparently, the interaction may be territorial. It does seem odd that pairs competing for territory would squabble over a carcass. It's a puzzle to me.

An immature Cooper's Hawk flew out over the water to harass a few floating Pigeon Guillemots but soon found itself surrounded by a flurry of highly aggressive, scrappy Purple Martins. Some of the Martins were even in full chase while still holding food in their bills. It's hard to say if the hawk learned any lessons from the encounter. Did it misjudge the size of the Pigeon Guillemots, or was it unprepared for the Purple Matins’ air defensive capabilities and response? Perhaps it was simply a case of hunting practice.

Une espèce extrêmement rare sur la Côte-Nord qui a donné tout un spectacle au groupe d'observateurs réunis pour le phénomène de correction migratoire.

DR followed and got some photos of the fresh juv. It flies okay but seems a bit clumsy; it looks like it is still growing in its outermost tail feathers. Media notes: Based on darker red eye color (v. female lighter orange/red eye color) & gray v. tan cheeks, I suspect this is an adult male.
Observation Details: Cooper's Hawk landed on lamp post at exactly 12:10 PM, which I got lots of pictures of. I knew right away it was either a Cooper's or Sharp-Shinned, so was taking as many pictures as possible, so could then determine which one. I then reviewed the article about how to tell difference between Cooper's and Sharp-Shinned, and I believe this is definitely a Cooper's Hawk. It also makes me confirm the hawk I saw several months ago, was likely a Sharp-Shinned, since it was so much smaller than this one and eyes were more owl-like, so went back and updated that one. Before sighting today, I actually think I heard it before seeing it, as I heard a high pitch screechy clicky kind of noise off in the distance and right as I was thinking to myself what it was, and thinking how it kind of sounded like it could be a bird of prey noise, suddenly all the pigeons and birds scattered and flapped their wings so loudly all at once, it just made a loud rumble almost like an earthquake, like it was confirming this. There was then a brief pause of silence, while I was looking around to see if any hawks around, and then as though it was entering theater stage left, it just swooped in and perched on the lamp post 25 ft from me and was eating it's lunch or using the lamp post as it's plucking stump. See photos. (WARNING: It was eating a bird, so some of the photos are graphic). UPDATE 7/3/21: I just discovered this is a male. According to a falconer on Reddit, who wrote: ""A question I get a lot is "how do you tell female Cooper's Hawks apart from males?" Key features are eye color (red-orange for females, blood red for males), auriculars/"cheek" color (tan in females, gray in males), back color (warm gray in females, blue-gray in males), plus look at head shape - female has longer skull, male has shorter bill."" -- [Based on this and a drawing with it, mine looks like an adult male v. female, especially eye color, so I will update it from adult sex unknown to being adult male.]

Media notes: Photo by MJ Keller
Observation Details: Per Paul Roberts: The new photos confirm my original impression and yours beyond any shadow of doubt. The front photo shows a typical imm Coop pattern of streaking much more refined than on an immature sharpie and very lightly marked on the belly. (Often Coop’s will have more delicate streaking than this, while sharpies have thicker more randomly shaped noodles.) If you magnify the tail in the photo, you’ll see that it is definitely rounded. Outer tail feathers much shorter than inner rectrices. Just tightly closed. It still looks a bit odd from underneath so it is possible it lost a rectrice (or two) that is just completing growing back in. The original photo showed the limitations of seeing a tightly closed tail from the back. Looking at the underneath view, you see why.  The second photo shows the flatter head and the hackles partially raised, so it looks much more Coop like (square-headed). (And the eyes front). The one anomaly left is that the clean white terminal tail band still looks pretty narrow for a Coop. Further magnified, it looks as though the white tips of the central rectrices might be abraided, as though the bird has spent considerable time perching on a concrete bridge stanchion or brick building, as these feather are no more than six months old. (Or maybe gravestones?)

I saw this fella fly past me to a tree. Watch it; then it flew to a power line. Watched it; then it flew on top of a bush. There were some sparrows in the bush. The hawk tried to reach one through the bush. It flattened out on the bush trying to grab one with it's talon. Then it flew down & ran into the bush from the ground & ran around the bush. While it was quite comical to see, i do hope he wasn't too hungry, because he left with nothing. I have never seen this before. It was playing cat & mouse with the sparrows. Initially i was quite surprised that the sparrows didn't fly off & leave the bush; but all seemed to end well for them so i guess it was a good decision.

Behaviors: Carrying Food; Courtship, Display, or Copulation; Vocalizing
Observation Details: Three seen simultaneously. One flew in to a pecan tree carrying prey, pursued by two others. Bird in photo 943 moved in on the ground and flew into the tree, displacing the holder of the carcass, the latter falling to the ground. The original 'owner' of the carcass then flew down to it, mantling and calling.   A Video of mantling bird at https://youtu.be/hV2ZnxIAZXk.  I don't know whether this interaction was of a mated pair, or a territorial scuffle between pairs which nest in the area. I haven't been able to sex the two - since they're the same size, apparently, the interaction may be territorial. It does seem odd that pairs competing for territory would squabble over a carcass. It's a puzzle to me.

Two observers on the deck when the Cooper's Hawk flew South along the hedges and landed in the Black Walnut 30' away (NOTE: I was wearing a florescent yellow jacket with reflective striping, and was probably visible from outer space).  After a few seconds, and maybe because I was moving to grab my camera, the Cooper's flew to a tree in the wild area.  Several minutes later it flew back near the Black Walnut, and was obviously on the hunt.  About two minutes later it flew through the dense hedges to an unseen perch for 2-3 minutes (20' away, but in dense hedges), then back to below the Walnut and eventually to an unseen location near the ground in the South hedges.  That was the last sighting.  About four minutes later I played several Cooper's Hawk and Sharp-shinned Hawk calls but got no response.

Observation Details: Unusual views from a couple of meters directly above; the immature hawk was hunting nearby feeders (mostly flocks of HOSP but also a number of MODOs around) and the pictures were taken immediately after a failed pass at some sparrows on the ground. The bird remained on the ground for a couple of minutes before relocating to the dense internal web of branches in a nearby small tree that frequently holds 100+ birds, where it was extremely concealed. No depredations observed. Immature but fairly large, I'd estimate it to be crow-sized; not sure if this suggests that it's a female.

I spotted the Cooper's Hawk that I've been seeing on and off for a few weeks. It was perched in usual tree. I went out and took some photos. I went inside and watched it for a minute, it flew towards front of house. I went out front and sure enough it was perched in maple. I got some poor photos and a few short videos. It was calling and then I heard another hawk also calling. I found it on top of house across street. They were no doubt interested in the House Sparrows that were chattering in bush out front. I snuck out the side door to try and get a photo of the other bird and or better photos of first bird. As I did, one of the hawks flew to the bush with the House Sparrows. I got some nice shots and a decent video. 4-6 minutes of lost productivity. I'll make it up.

1590 St. Clair Pkwy, Courtright, Ontario, CA (42.816, -82.475)
Observation Details: Cooper's hawk back again; first flew into the yard, eyes on a mourning dove in the grass; unsuccessful, he perched while everything scattered, then flew to the driveway beside a dense, prickly bush where dozens of sparrows were hiding, absolutely quiet. He watched the bush "like a hawk" before attacking it as in the earlier incident -- and I was astounded at those sparrows inside not making one move or sound. Thwarted, the hawk retreated to the top of the bush for a few long minutes, then took his leave. And still, the sparrows remained absolutely silent!  After at least 10 minutes, a few birds appeared on the edges, looked around, and eventually left. Then more braved an exit from the hideout until all were out. It was quite the show. And I am completely impressed with the sparrows not giving away their locations with the danger so clear and present.

Locality: Riparian Preserve at Gilbert Water Ranch

Observation Details: My mom and I were sitting down to eat some lunch when she spotted a hawk landing in our small creek. She thought it might be a RSHA, but I grabbed the camera and saw that it was a Cooper's. It stood in the shallow end of the creek for a bit, drinking then tipping its beak up towards the sky. It didn't seem to be bothered by the collection of bees buzzing around at its feet. I walked outside and got a few photos, then it flew away after a minute to perch about 20 feet up in a pine tree on the edge of the yard. Last year, the COHAs enjoyed this spot, which strengthens the possibility of it being the same hawk (perhaps - or perhaps it's just a nice spot for them). It sat there for about five minutes, letting me take pictures of it, and fully aware of my presence, as it kept looking directly at me. Eventually, it jumped up flew off.   VERY large for a Cooper's, so most likely a female - although the blue/gray coloration on the back would suggest male. And it had a rather small head that almost gave it the appearance of a Sharpie. Overall size, however, confirms adult female COHA.

Media notes: Épervier de Cooper
Observation Details: Un jeune Épervier est repéré sur le chemin du retour dans le même secteur de nidification que l'an dernier. Il est perché, bien dégagé et il me regarde. Pendant quelques minutes, l'oiseau s'étire, fait sa toilette et se déplaça d'arbres en arbres en montant les branches. J'entends à quelques reprises son cri caractéristique à intervalle régulier (un genre de sifflet grinçant). Après plusieurs minutes de recherches à l'extérieur du boisé, je ne peux confirmer la présence des adultes ni même l'endroit exact du nid.  L'oiseau est costaud et ses tarses sont forts. Il possède des yeux de couleurs jaunâtres, les couvertures sont brunes marbré de quelques plumes blanches. Les rémiges primaires de l'aile sont longues, larges et bien arrondies. Les rectrices externes sont plus courtes me permettant d'observer un étagement des plumes de la queue qui se termine par une bande blanche bien visible. La queue prend alors un aspect rond qui élimine l’Épervier brun.  Les rayures de la queue sont égales,et les sous caudales sont parfaitement blanches ce qui élimine l’Autour des palombes. Il s'agit bien d'un Épervier de Cooper (juvénile).

All photos taken through the window by Bob Cashen and Marlene Cashen.  We first saw the Cooper's perched on a branch of a maple tree in the back yard at 1:50 p.m.  Around 2:04 p.m. a gray squirrel began to taunt the hawk and began approaching the hawk on the branch where it was perched, which caused the bristling and wing flaring of the hawk towards the squirrel.  The squirrel went to a higher branch in the tree above the hawk, where the hawk is looking intently up at the squirrel.  Finally, the hawk seemed to have enough of that brazen squirrel and flew to another tree in the back yard where he wouldn't be bothered anymore.  It wasn't until 2:20 p.m. that the hawk flew off -- still hungry!  So we were able to watch all the activity and interactions for 30 minutes.

Observation Details: Cooper Hawk made an attack on Doves then landed on a power line.

I was back in the kitchen at 8:30 looking out the window and seeing only a handful of birds on the driveway at the seed and the feeders.  Rather they were mostly sitting in the Styrax tree (very dense understory tree) next to the driveway.  I looked up and there was the Cooper's Hawk.  See the first picture.  This time he was sitting in the neighbor's Catalpa tree, which is planted right next to the Elm - both right along side our property line.  I continued watching the birds warily coming to the feeder and coming to the ground under the Styrax and continuing craning my neck to get an angle on the Hawk.  Right at 8:40 when I looked out the window for the Cooper's - wow, there were TWO of them.  I'd put the camera away and had to go get it and got back in time to grab one picture (see second picture).  I only got this one picture and then the bird on the right flew off while I was trying to take another picture.  The bird on the left stayed (the single bird in the 1st picture) stayed for a few more minutes.  At 8:50 he was gone.      So there is a pair of Cooper's, presumably.  I know male Cooper's tend to be smaller than females but it is difficult to see significant size difference between these two in the second picture.  Except, I think the one on the left is more fluffed up and, hence, perhaps the smaller of the two.  So I'm calling the left one male and the right one female.  There is obviously significant difference in coloration of the two birds.  The left (male) bird is much paler.  The right bird (female?) has much more red coloration.  I don't know if coloration helps sex Cooper's.       I have looked back at the many pictures I have taken of a Cooper's Hawk the last month (going back into December 2018).  Almost every time I've seen one I've uploaded a picture.  Looking back at the pictures I think many times (especially the last several times) I think I have been taking pictures of the bird with all the red coloration, the bird that I'm calling the female (the bird on the right in the second picture).          I can't recall seeing or reporting two Cooper's at the same time before the last 4-5 years, unless it was two juveniles or a parent with juvenile.        A pair of Cooper's has nested in the neighborhood just two block away for the last several years so I'm guessing this pair is them.

Observation Details: I was watching a non-breeding SPSA on the eastern back of the Pack River. Suddenly it give extended alarm calls and flew out over the river towards the opposite bank.  This juvenile COHA came streaking out of the sun from the east and caught up with the SPSA mid-stream.  There was a great splash, and the SPSA came up out of the water flying back towards the eastern bank.  The COHA flew up to a perch on the west bank, where I took these photos.  There were no feathers in the water, and the COHA did not appear to be wet.  The SPSA flew across the eastern sandy area and into thick brush at its edge.

Locality: Scott Ave NW, Grand Rapids, MI
Observation Details: Observed bird for about an hour, starting at about 09:50. The Cooper's Hawk had caught a small bird, probably a House Sparrow, and flew to a horizontal limb of a Catalpa in our backyard where I observed it feeding on the sparrow for about 20 minutes. After it was done, the hawk walked a few feet on the limb, spent a couple of minutes cleaning its bill on the limb, then perched motionless for another 20 minutes. While the hawk was feeding, a Northern Cardinal landed on a branch about 20 feet overhead, and remained for about ten minutes, with each bird seemingly unaware of the other.

Media notes: Fourth-cycle female based on plumage and banding information.
Observation Details: A fluffy female perched in tree directly above entrance to trail, unconcerned by pedestrians below. We stopped to look at her, and when she stretched, James noticed a band!  After about fifteen minutes of waiting and watching from all angles, we managed to identify all nine digits on the band: 2206-91815. She was banded as a juvenile on January 3rd, 2018 by somebody at the Owl Foundation in Vineland!

At one point the larger hawk sprinted after a squirrel into a bush, which was quite funny to see.  Met Heather and Calvin (apologies if I misspelt your name!), and we discussed the prospects of the smaller one perhaps being a Sharp-shinned Hawk.

Observation Details: Assuming one bird was adult female with "whe-ya" cries, gray mantle, and barred-red breast. Both birds had songbird in talons. One bird made repeated visits to nest. The tree trunk and area under nest is splattered with fresh looking bird poop. The nest twigs appear to be covered with downy feathers. I thought both birds were adults but I could be wrong: only one bird was easy to see, the other flying about in treetops. Loud and chaotic in the park. The hawks were also deterring a pair of ravens that kept to the park perimeter. They didn't like when I looked at the nest so I took and seat and waited for them to fly around. 6/27/2018: After being able to observe the juveniles I'm thinking these were the adults. I'm not sure the juveniles could fly that quickly through treetops with prey in their talons. The adults were probably freaking out over the ravens that were showing a lot of interest in their activities. I think the juveniles were in hiding.

Observation Details: Adult eating a rat! I heard a Steller's Jay giving an alarm call inside a willow thicket, so I crawled inside to investigate. I found this adult Cooper's Hawk perched very low to the ground. Accipiter's are usually so flighty, I couldn't believe that it stayed! I sat down and watched it for almost 30 minutes as it moved from perch to perch, often so close that I could not fit the whole bird in the frame! It flew across the opening in the thicket a couple of times, passing very close to my head. Eventually, it grabbed a rat from a branch just a couple feet from my head! It ate the rat right in the thicket while I watched. What an amazing encounter!

Observation Details: The tail had me going on this one, but everything else says Cooper's Hawk, which was my initial impression in the field. Size was on the cusp too - didn't seem big enough to be a Northern Goshawk. While the first photo shows uneven banding on the tail indicative of Goshawk, the color overall is more orange-buff overall, especially on the head, rather than the overall darker colors of a Northern Goshawk. In addition, there isn't enough streaking underneath, especially between the tail and the breast. There is a hint of a superciliary line in the second photo, but it's the wrong color - orange-buff rather than white, and it isn't as prominent as on most Northern Goshawks. I haven't seen that unevenness in the tail of a Coop before, but perhaps it's just the way the tail feathers are folded.

Wavered on this ID for a bit. Initial impression in the field was Cooper's Hawk but later review of photos shook the confidence in that ID. After review with various raptor experts, Coop was agreed upon by all. While not an accipiter showing all textbook ID marks, it certainly showed a blocky head - not ice cream scoop-ish like a Sharpie's. Eyes are small and set more forward - not buggy or goofy looking. Orbital ridge showed more prominently from other angles. Tail tip has no hard corners and white tip on outermost feathers lines up with darker band, suggesting graduation of feathers. Could not see streaking on center breast, however, the visible edge of breast streaking show the more clearly defined diamond/tear shapes of a Coop rather than the typical messy blobs of a Sharpie, getting paler closer to the legs.
They appeared to be building a nest in the large oak in back of the Nature Center.  They were pulling twigs from the tree and kept returning to the same spot in the tree.

One bird circling near white barn, causing starling murmurations, seen again later being harassed by crows. Two separate birds, a smaller one missing primary feathers and a much larger one were seen loosely associating about 8:30 am, flying above opposite side of the field and over houses to the southwest. They were flying in an unusual manner, the smaller one making fast, at times undulating, moves with deep quick wing beats (at first I thought it was a nighthawk). Both birds had bright white feathers ruffled out between the wings and tail. As they flew back over the field I photographed them, and the larger one appeared to have a dark mask with pale supercillium and a reddish eye. The pictures, combined with the other unusual details and behavior I had not seen before made me think they were Northern Goshawks. When I got home later and reviewed and opened the photos on my computer, it was clear that the barring on the breast was reddish, not gray and the mask and ruffled white feathers near the tail were misleading. As for the unusual flight, it did appear to be some type of courtship or territorial behavior.

Observation Details: My mom and I were sitting down to eat some lunch when she spotted a hawk landing in our small creek. She thought it might be a RSHA, but I grabbed the camera and saw that it was a Cooper's. It stood in the shallow end of the creek for a bit, drinking then tipping its beak up towards the sky. It didn't seem to be bothered by the collection of bees buzzing around at its feet. I walked outside and got a few photos, then it flew away after a minute to perch about 20 feet up in a pine tree on the edge of the yard. Last year, the COHAs enjoyed this spot, which strengthens the possibility of it being the same hawk (perhaps - or perhaps it's just a nice spot for them). It sat there for about five minutes, letting me take pictures of it, and fully aware of my presence, as it kept looking directly at me. Eventually, it jumped up flew off.   VERY large for a Cooper's, so most likely a female - although the blue/gray coloration on the back would suggest male. And it had a rather small head that almost gave it the appearance of a Sharpie. Overall size, however, confirms adult female COHA.

Looked out to see a large, adult Cooper's on the top of the peanut feeder shepherd's hook. It stayed there several minutes, then flew into the arborvitae. Shortly after that, it flew out to sit in the top of one of the large viburnums just to the east of the arborvitaes, where she continued to sit for about an hour, flying away at 12:45 p.m. At least 8 cardinals were in the shrubbery, as was a chickadee, which came within 20' of the hawk. Eventually, the cardinals started to slowly return to the main feeder in the middle of the yard, ignoring the Cooper's, which ignored them. The House Sparrows returned, too, while the hawk was present, in plain view. A few other species were seen close to this time and are included on this checklist.

An adult female came in and landed looked around attentively suddenly swooped down up and around and caught a female Cassin’s finch on the ground. Took it up into the spruce tree and proceeded to pluck and eat it. Came back into the feeder area and perched looking around and suddenly swooping down and giving chase, persistently, until catching another female Cassin’s finch.  Both finches were enlarged and not flying well. This time the hawk flew off out of sight with it’s prey. Less than half an hour later it was back and spent considerable time perched looking around. It even flew down to the ground and circled the Oregon grape bush under the feeders. Finally gave up and flew off. About three minutes later or less the little birds were back at the feeders. Then suddenly the alarm went up and they were gone. Then a juvenile coopers hawk flew in and perched right above the tube feeder. Just as I raised my binoculars it flew pell-mell through the breezeway chased by the adult Cooper’s Hawk!Quite the afternoon of hawk feeding and watching!

Observation Details: I wrestled a bit with the ID of this immature accipiter, but wound up going with Cooper's instead of Sharpie. Overall, when perched, the head seems fairly proportionally sized to the body, it has that somewhat "mean" look versus "surprised" look of a Sharpie, also the tarsi ("shins") and toes seem quite robust. In flight, the tail appears quite long and the head projection is well beyond the wings. Hence, though a few field marks suggest immature Sharpie (e.g. breast streaking quite thick and not tapering off towards the belly, tail tip seemed more squarish in the field, though photos do show slight rounding of a Cooper’s), in aggregate, it seems most field marks point to Cooper's rather than Sharpie for this bird, overall structure wins out in this case.

Immature bird, hunting sparrows in back yard brush piles. Regarding Cooper's ID, which I based solely on these photos: Cooper's Hawks nest nearby and visit this yard occasionally. This bird has globular streaking that seems to go way down the belly, and its back doesn't seem to have a contrasty nape, all of which argue against Cooper's. However: I measured the fence top rail where the bird is perched and calculated the bird's length. It's at least 16 inches. Sharp-shinneds are said to top out at 13.4 inches.

Our young COHA siblings continue to try their skills at hunting. They mostly stay on the canal and appear to hunt together. They are quiet and still now while searching for food, except last night when they called louder than I have ever heard them call. I would surmise they were pretty hungry and were calling for help from a parent bird. This am they went after a squirrel in the yard. One chased the squirrel over the fence and then the other went after him. The squirrel at times would stand still with his tail over his head as if for protection and other times run. The squirrel finally hid in a tree. The hunt was not successful but the other yard birds were very aware and feared the raptors staying away. The COHA (pics) on the fence didn't participate as much as the one pictured on the ground and in the tree. Update 8:50 one COHA is sitting in open view on the fence and birds are on the feeder. The chase is probably the only thing that frightened the feeder birds earlier.

Observation Details: Immature.  Large, tail rounded in flight.  Head and neck tawny, head square, lots of white mottling on the back. The placement of the eye seems consistent with what's often said about placement in the Cooper's Hawk versus the Sharpshin (namely that it's close to the bill in the Cooper's and more towards the center of the head in the Sharpshin), but I always have trouble with that feature.  It's hard to make much of the tail from the photos.  It shows a rather thin whitish band at the tip, and the folded tail does not appear rounded (though what's showing in the photos are, I assume, the inmost feathers, which are concealing the shorter ones).  I note, though, that the bird seems very long-tailed, the wing tips barely reaching the top of the third dark band (counting from the tip).

I was pretty sure it was either a Cooper's or sharp-shinned based on the size and long tail but left it as hawk sp. until I could check the photos.  I believe based on the head size/shape, the dark chest barring, and the slightly rounded tail that this is a Cooper's Hawk.

Seen together next to the walkway that gets submerged during high tide. Striking size difference between the two.   When they didn't fend off crows, they seemed to figure out how to chase ground squirrels. The squirrels didn't seem too concerned, and easily got away from the somewhat awkward approaches of the hawks. At one point the larger hawk sprinted after a squirrel into a bush, which was quite funny to see.  Met Heather and Calvin (apologies if I misspelt your name!), and we discussed the prospects of the smaller one perhaps being a Sharp-shinned Hawk.

An immature Cooper's Hawk flew out over the water to harass a few floating Pigeon Guillemots but soon found itself surrounded by a flurry of highly aggressive, scrappy Purple Martins. Some of the Martins were even in full chase while still holding food in their bills. It's hard to say if the hawk learned any lessons from the encounter. Did it misjudge the size of the Pigeon Guillemots, or was it unprepared for the Purple Matins’ air defensive capabilities and response? Perhaps it was simply a case of hunting practice.

super cool encounter!!! after watching the delaware river, went back going east towards the trail area when I saw an accipiter flying low about 2-3m off the ground heading north from somewhere near the forest edge and then perching on cross structure at the south end of the bridge over the aqueduct, got some photos immediately before walking up to it. to my surprised, one cyclist and another walking person passed right by it, probably 2-3 m from it since its perch was just on the side of the road about 3 m high, and when i got there it didn't fly away immediately either. However when I got camera and stayed there to take photos it probably felt uncomfortable and moved to another perch about 5 m away, but I could still get photos there. it stayed for about 30 seconds before going far away on tall on trees north of the creek of the aqueduct. from this experience I feel like I've learned that sometimes if you just walk by a bird it doesn't fly away but once you stop and look at it, even if you don't move or do anything, it will fly away, so better pretend you're not focusing you attention on them!!  also my best photos of a cooper's hawk yet

West D Greenway & Alton Baker Eastgate Woodlands (I-5 to Riverview Blvd.)
Observation Details: Adult eating a rat! I heard a Steller's Jay giving an alarm call inside a willow thicket, so I crawled inside to investigate. I found this adult Cooper's Hawk perched very low to the ground. Accipiter's are usually so flighty, I couldn't believe that it stayed! I sat down and watched it for almost 30 minutes as it moved from perch to perch, often so close that I could not fit the whole bird in the frame! It flew across the opening in the thicket a couple of times, passing very close to my head. Eventually, it grabbed a rat from a branch just a couple feet from my head! It ate the rat right in the thicket while I watched. What an amazing encounter!

Observation Details: the gang was still hanging out near the nest tree - 1 was in a tree by itself and the other 3 were perched together a few feet apart in another tree while 1 of them chowed down on a Rock Pigeon that had perhaps been recently delivered because all were calling back and forth at that time  after a few minutes, the diner dropped its lunch to the ground with a thunk but everyone must have been full because it laid on the ground untouched for some time before anyone bothered to fly down to it which gave us the opportunity to examine it and see that only the head had been shredded and eaten, the neck had been plucked down to bare skin, and the body was untouched except for talon puncture holes  eventually what appeared to be the same diner flew down to the sizable victim and looked up at the branch it had fallen from as if estimating whether it could be carried back up, but after dragging it a couple yards with one foot, settled for ground dining

some notes on the progress of this nest first observed in April:  16 Apr - pair sat side by side on branch of nest tree, then female went to nest  18 Apr - female on nest in morning, absent in afternoon during ruckus from excavation for new sidewalk below  19 Apr - both male and female present, possible copulation, vocal exchange, then female went to nest  May - female was consistently sitting on nest during periodic re-checks  16 Jun - 1 fluffy white chick seen in nest with mom   23 Jun - 3 chicks confirmed in photo of nest, male dashed in and out lickety-split to deliver prey to female at nest

Perched off Creekside Trail where it meets main trail near entrance. At first, I was stumped by this observation despite excellent look. i originally identified it as Sharp-shinned because of what appeared to be rounded head and squared-off tail. But long tail, short wings and prominent black cap are good for Cooper's. Smaller than crow, bigger than robin, but within size range of both species. Sharp-shinned is rare in this part of San Diego County, while Cooper's are prevalent in Blue Sky. Though I'd love to be able to report a Sharpie here, this is a Cooper's. Comments welcome. 33.016577, -117.020123 Second Cooper's found in nest along main trail to Lake Ramona. Identified by kek call.

My neighbor texted that the hawk was just in his coop attacking his chickens and is now roosting on his back deck looking for more chickens.  Update at 1607. Observation Details: Initially seen sitting on the limb near the brush pile @ 1632 hrs, where the House Sparrows typically congregate. Bird was there after I saw it for 24 minutes continuously turning it's head looking for birds. Stretched it's wings and tail shortly before leaving, flying away to the east just north of the house @ 1656 hrs. An adult Cooper's Hawk landed in the north treeline the following day but only stayed for 1-2 minutes before leaving. A Dark-eyed Junco landed in an Amelanchier behind the hawk @ 1652 hrs and was nervously scanning the area where the feed was. It remained perched until it left @ 1710 hrs, @ 15 minutes after the hawk left. No birds were seen feeding on the ground tonight after the hawk left, which is typically a busy time for them. Short video of it scanning

All photos taken through the window by Bob Cashen and Marlene Cashen.  We first saw the Cooper's perched on a branch of a maple tree in the back yard at 1:50 p.m.  Around 2:04 p.m. a gray squirrel began to taunt the hawk and began approaching the hawk on the branch where it was perched, which caused the bristling and wing flaring of the hawk towards the squirrel.  The squirrel went to a higher branch in the tree above the hawk, where the hawk is looking intently up at the squirrel.  Finally, the hawk seemed to have enough of that brazen squirrel and flew to another tree in the back yard where he wouldn't be bothered anymore.  It wasn't until 2:20 p.m. that the hawk flew off -- still hungry!  So we were able to watch all the activity and interactions for 30 minutes.
Flew into our yard right unto the ground under low hanging branches of a spruce tree and caught a sparrow.

"On my walk through the park yesterday (12/29/2010) I saw this hawk sitting in the water, in the shallow pool just north of Azalea pond. I'm not sure what kind it is--it's about 15-16 inches from head to tail. Maybe a young Cooper's? It didn't see to be in any distress, and it wasn't really bathing (ducked its head under a couple of times in the half-hour I was watching), just ... sitting.I have no idea What it was doing. The fellow who pointed him out to me though maybe he was waiting for rats to come out on the bank. Maybe he was fishing? The pool is fed from a pipe, maybe the water was warm?The hawk sat for a half hour. When we heard sirens from the West Side, he became a little agitated and called, a even-toned keee-errr. Finally he flew up into a tree and thence elsewhere."

As I turned onto my street where I live I spotted a couple of crows behaving like there was a raptor nearby, and there was!  It was a COHA and it turned the tables on the crows from being harassed to being the aggressor viciously chasing one of the crows.  After the crows left, the COWA perched in a tree and I was able get a couple of photos in good late afternoon light.  Then the bird flew across the street into another tree and I got a couple more photos (it didn't seem to mind me) and then it went to another tree where a second, larger COHA was perched.  Got a couple of photos of the second bird too.  The first two photos are of the first COHA and the rest are the second, larger COHA.  When the two COHA were together in the same tree the female made the "whaa" vocalization for food from the smaller male I presume.

Observation Details: An adult and two HY birds seen near the upper end of the stream. After we'd seen one juv Cooper's fly by and keep going out of the immediate area, we then saw and heard a calling (occasionally) adult Cooper's. We were slowly birding our way in the direction of where we eventually saw the adult (perched relatively low in a Eucalyptus). Oddly enough it remained on its perch even when we were getting quite close, which I thought was a little strange--even knowing they can seem to be relatively tolerant of people at times (especially in a setting like this, with frequent park visitors). Finally, now within maybe 30 or so feet of the adult COHA, a second HY COHA flushed up from along the creek (hidden in the weeds in the area of the "watering hole", presumably getting a drink).  After the HY bird flew off, at that point the adult finally took off.  So I'd have to guess this was a local breeder still being protective over it's fledglings, even though they seemed to be foraging on their own. It sure seemed odd seeing this adult not appear like it was going to budge, along with it giving the occasional, loud "kek-kek-kek-kek-kek-kek!"; definitely seemed reminiscent of a bird that was still involved with nesting duties. However, at this date it didn't seem possible for a COHA to have an active nest, and even seemed a bit late to have dependent fledglings. But when the HY bird flushed up from the stream near us, it all seemed to suggest there was still some connection between the adult and presumably one of its fledglings.

Proportionally large head and suggestion of light nape -- along with prevalence of Cooper's on the Rice campus -- point to Cooper's rather than Sharp-shinned.  The remainder of this comment is something of a test of Sibley's mark,  "adult male Cooper's has gray cheeks (orange on all others)" (including adult female Cooper's).  The first question is, what is the color on the cheeks of this Cooper's?  I would say it is orange washed with gray, especially higher up, below the eye and behind the eye, but to some extent over the whole cheek area.   Given this mixed conclusion, I looked at eBird photos of adult Cooper's Hawks, first those marked male, and then those marked female.  The result?  There was absolutely no clear separation based on cheek color.  A whole range of colors was represented both in the male and the female group.  The range in cheek color I found (again, present in photos of both male and female adult Cooper's) ran from very pale gray (nearly white) to gray, to a mixture of gray and orange, and finally to orange. (Size is of course another differentiating mark.  The photo does not allow judgment on this point, and I have little recollection of my impressions at the time of viewing, other than the feeling that it was not really small, that is, not the size of a male Sharp-shinned Hawk.)
Observation Details: Sex unknown, though the bird appeared on the large end of the scale, and so probably a female.

Observation Details: This bird was hunting White-crowned Sparrows in 7-foot pomegranate trees before flying to this nearby post. This ID is from Jon Dunn, based on photos here: "It's a Cooper's Hawk. In this photo, the bird has a slightly bulky look (subjective) and is out in the open.  Although both Sharp-shinned and Cooper’s can sit in the open, Sharpies tend to go for cover thus making photography very difficult. The head on this bird is rather blocky and the eyes placed forward. The head actually looks big relative to the body while the Sharpie looks small headed. The tarsi or legs look thick. Sharpies have pencil thin legs. Still this is subjective. There is a rufous tone on the top and back of the head and the on the throat. This is often hard to see but is visible in your photo."  Re breast plumage: "In the photo, the dark, very distinct streaks are at the top of the breast. Usually, this continues down the breast in Cooper’s Hawks. However in the photo, the major part of the breast has rufous spots and streaks, which are clean and distinct. One of the things to look for in a Sharpie is rufous, smudgy streaks. Had you gotten this photo at a straight on view rather than a side view, it would have been even more difficult to i.d. due to the rufous streaks. Still, I’m convinced it is a Cooper’s Hawk."

This bird was hunting White-crowned Sparrows in 7-foot pomegranate trees before flying to this nearby post. This ID is from Jon Dunn, based on photos here: "It's a Cooper's Hawk. In this photo, the bird has a slightly bulky look (subjective) and is out in the open.  Although both Sharp-shinned and Cooper’s can sit in the open, Sharpies tend to go for cover thus making photography very difficult. The head on this bird is rather blocky and the eyes placed forward. The head actually looks big relative to the body while the Sharpie looks small headed. The tarsi or legs look thick. Sharpies have pencil thin legs. Still this is subjective. There is a rufous tone on the top and back of the head and the on the throat. This is often hard to see but is visible in your photo."  Re breast plumage: "In the photo, the dark, very distinct streaks are at the top of the breast. Usually, this continues down the breast in Cooper’s Hawks. However in the photo, the major part of the breast has rufous spots and streaks, which are clean and distinct. One of the things to look for in a Sharpie is rufous, smudgy streaks. Had you gotten this photo at a straight on view rather than a side view, it would have been even more difficult to i.d. due to the rufous streaks. Still, I’m convinced it is a Cooper’s Hawk."

Media notes: Épervier de Cooper
Observation Details: Juvénile quittant le boisé pour prendre une thermique et tournoie au-dessus de moi pour se diriger direction Est. La queue est longue par rapport à la longueur des ailes ce qui me fait réaliser qu'il s'agit du groupe des Accipiter. Les rayures de la queue sont égaux, sans zigzag, les sous-caudales sont parfaitement blanches éliminant l'autour des palombes. Rectrices externes plus courtes permettant d'observer un étagement des plumes de la queue se terminant par une bande blanche bien visible. La queue prend un aspect bien rond qui élimine l'épervier brun.
